Small, thin flan of bronze. No decoration evident on either obverse or reverse.

Additional Notes:  Identified as a coin when excavated. The weight, however, does not correspond to any Republican denomination. At less than a gram, it is still too light for the very small half-litra denomination, of which Crawford identifies a single issue RRC 26/4 (234-231 BCE).  Despite this, given the longevity of use for the other coins found in this context, it is possible that this piece of bronze was used in a manner similar to small denominations of bronze and functioned as currency based solely on its weight.

Head of Mercury, wearing winged petasos, right. Top of chlamys visible at base of neck. Border of dots.
Prow of ship, right. ROMA, above. Solid border.

Δ238b
Related to RRC 16/1a
AE				Denomination: Double litra (?)
Diameter: 20 mm		Weight:10.94 g
Mint: Uncertain South Italian		Date Range: 1st quarter of the 3rd century BCE
Authority: Anonymous

Head of Apollo, fillet not visible, right. Border of dots.
Poorly preserved. Left back leg, underside, and right foreleg of animal, walking right, discernible. 

Notes: Obverse type resembles BM 1889,1106.139 with respect to the arrangement of hair on the top of the head and the shape of the nose. However, arrangement of hair above the brow differs. The deity is perhaps wearing a laurel or other type of vegetal crown. The obverse was also struck off flan, obscuring the hair at the nape of the neck. A secure identification is further complicated by corrosion on the obverse. 
The stance of the animal on the reverse resembles the arrangement of the walking lions on RRC 16/1a. 
If the identification is correct, the weight is above average for the double litra but within the weight range for this denomination.
Found by metal detectorist.

Found in lab. male and female pair. scene in 3 fragments. weight 0.046 kg.
Edited by Amy Welch 2017. Found in three sherds, reattached by a conservator. Erotic scene in fairly high relief, depicting kneeling man and reclining woman. Most of the man is preserved. His ankles are crossed behind him, and he grabs the woman's left ankle with his right hand. His left hand is just visible behind his torso, grasping the woman's right calf with her right foot under his armpit. His chin is pointed down toward his chest. The woman reclines with her legs up as previously described. Part of her torso and right breast are preserved, as is her right arm, which stretches upward and behind her head, of which only a small bit of hair remains. A piece of cloth is visible beneath the man's feet. At the far left of the sherd is the end of a possible inscription, with only the final V" or "Y" visible. Vegetal and looping patterns decorate the upper potions of the scene in horizontal rows. Also of interest is the fact that the figures have six fingers and toes
SF_OBJECT_TYPE: where visible. The size of the figures indicates that there could have been three such scenes decorating the cup if they were placed fairly close together

SF_DESCRIPTION: Bronze swastika plaques, bosses, and springs from T.53
SF_NOTES:
Microexcavated out of SU3624 in conservation. location in clumps was noted and marked and pieces are now associated with subdivisions of this find in relatin to where on the body they were discovered. A small number near the head, some on the main trunk, some towards one side, some on the legs. A map/plan of this exists as made by Sara and Anna when they excavated the pieces. Some joins may be across this general division due to post-depositional agents (worms) that dispersed the bronze and fragmented it, so this should be taken as a general guide rather than strict assessment. Some pieces are too small to be reconstructed, like parts of bosses, but are recognisable as such. Some pieces of this shroud were found outside SU3624 before this section was bulk-excavated. 
Includes plaques, bosses, springs and tiny cylinders,

Microexcavated from SU3624 along with all the bronze plaques (Delta2040) and bulla (Delta2039). Likely formed part of a little necklace.

SF_DESCRIPTION: blue glass pendant in the shape of a jug
SF_NOTES:
Glass pendant made up of a sphere and attached ring. The sphere is partially pierced and the ring is attached next to this hole, so that the whole object resembles a globular jug with a curved strap handle.
Examples of similar miniature glass jug pendants are known from the Corning Museum of Glass and seem to date to the 3rd and 4th centuries CE (for Roman examples).

2 amber objects: Each roughly 2 x 1 x .5 cm. The more stable piece seems to have been worked. See photos for more details. Both pieces are now stored in tinfoil to protect them from additional damage. (Should not be stored in the Finds Lab w A/C).

Conservation treatment 6th July 2017
Two Amber fragments with degraded surface removed from soil. Surface actively laminating off object.
Amber examined under a microscope and dry brushed lightly.
One Amber fragment left unconsolidated for provenance testing.
Larger Amber fragment with possible shaped round edges consolidated with paraloid b72 (unknown percentage but less than 20) in acrtone through immersion. Object left in paraloid until no more bubbles appeared. Excess paraloid removed with acetone and left to air dry.
Both fragments wrapped in tin foil and sealed in an unpierced box. Flakes of Amber also kept with the fragments in an unpierced bag.

Recommendations: Amber must be kept out of direct light and at a stable relative humidity (45-60% outer limit, ideally 50-55%) to prevent drying out and cracking.

SF_DESCRIPTION: Mixed metal weight with figural element
SF_NOTES:
Rounded lead weight attached to bottom of bronze portrait head in the round, with partially preserved iron hook on top of head; lead sheets wrapped around the base of the bronze attachment; the head appears to be moldmade in solid bronze. The portrait is of a youthful male figure with wavy hair, parted in the center of the forehead, and wearing a helmet(?) with ram's horns; the head is slightly tilted to the right with an upturned gaze. The style of the portrait is Hellenistic, and resembles portraits of Alexander the Great as Zeus Ammon.
Part of Caroline N's 2018 Finds School Project.
